Predicting Two-Stories Prices in NY

Emmanuel Messori

30/09/2021

Objective

In this Project, we will use property sales data from all five boroughs of New York City:

  • Bronx
  • Brooklyn
  • Manhattan
  • Staten Island
  • Queens

Our purpose is to explore the following questions:

  1. How well does the size of a property (measured in gross square feet) explain or predict sale price across New York City as a whole?
  • To answer this, well explore property sales data for all five boroughs combined.
  1. How well does the size of a property explain or predict sale price for each individual borough?
  • For this question, well build, analyze, and compare linear models for each borough.

The Data

We ll work with Rolling Sales Data The Department of Finances Rolling Sales files lists properties that sold in the last twelve-month period in New York City for tax class 1, 2, and 4. These files include:

  • the neighborhood;
  • building type;
  • square footage;
  • other data.

Property Sales Terms

A glossary of Property Sales terms explains words and phrases used in each file.

Term Meaning
Borough name of the borough
Neighborhood name assigned by the dep. of finance
BC Category broad usage of the property
Tax Class one of four different tax classes
Block borough subdivision
Lot subdivision of a tax block
Easement right to make limited use of another property
Building Class propertys constructive use
Address street address
Zip Code postal code
Residential Units n units
Commercial Units n units
Total Units n units
Land Square Feet land area
Gross Square Feet total area of all the floors including land area
Year built year of construction
Sales Price sale price in $
$0 Sales Price transfer without cash consideration ?

We can then bind the data by row:

NYsales <- bind_rows(manhattan, bronx, brooklyn, queens, statenisland)
rm(bronx, brooklyn, manhattan, queens, statenisland)
# col names to lower
NYsales %>%
    rename_with(~tolower(gsub(" ", "_", .x, fixed = TRUE))) -> NYsales
# substitute borough number with the respective name for clarity
NYsales %>%
    mutate(borough = case_when(borough == 1 ~ "manhattan", borough == 2 ~ "bronx",
        borough == 3 ~ "brooklyn", borough == 4 ~ "queens", borough == 5 ~ "staten_island")) ->
    NYsales

# convert capitalized text to title
NYsales %>%
    mutate(across(c(neighborhood, building_class_category, address), str_to_title)) ->
    NYsales

We can safely drop the easement column given its empty.

NYsales %>%
    select(-easement) -> NYsales

We will now :

  1. filter out the property exchanges between family members - we assume the threshold to be $10,000.
  2. Remove observations with gross square footage of zero.
  3. Since were interested in studying the relationship between gross_square_feet and sale_price, we will drop the NA values present in the first variable.
NYsales %>%
    filter(sale_price >= 10000 & gross_square_feet != 0) %>%
    drop_na(gross_square_feet) %>%
    arrange(borough, neighborhood) -> NYsales_c

The gross_square_feet variable has 38543 NAs and 2016 O values. We have also rnrow(filter(NYsales, sale_price < 10000))` transaction of less than 10000$. After filtering for these conditions, the resulting data frame has less than a half of the row of the starting one:

Correlation between gross_square_feet and sale_price

To visualize the relationship between to the two variable we will generate a scatter plot faceted by neighborhood:

ggplot(NYsales_c, aes(gross_square_feet, sale_price)) + geom_point() + scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) + facet_wrap(~borough, scales = "free") +
    theme_minimal()

Visualizing the data this way for all the property types is not very meaningful, because we have a very large range of prices and areas. We will therefore concentrate on two stories (category A1), which is the most popular building class:

# filter for A1 and remove the only two stories in Manhattan
NYsales_c %>%
    filter(building_class_at_time_of_sale == "A1" & borough != "manhattan") ->
    NY_twostories

NY_twostories %>%
    ggplot(aes(gross_square_feet, sale_price)) + geom_point(aes(color = borough),
    alpha = 0.5) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
    theme_minimal() + ggtitle("Relationship between gross square feet and price",
    subtitle = "Two stories")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

There is an evident linear relationship between the two variables. Anyway we have some strong outliers in the mid-range area, the majority of them being Brooklyn properties. Lets try to plot again this relationship by excluding sale prices above 3750000:

NY_twostories %>%

    limits = c(0, 3750000)) + theme_minimal() + ggtitle("Relationship between gross square feet and price",

Generating multiple models

We will now use the map function with the nest and tidy functions to generate multiple linear regression models by borough.

library(broom)
NY_twostories %>%
    group_by(borough) %>%
    nest() %>%
    mutate(linearmod = map(data, ~lm(sale_price ~ gross_square_feet, data = .))) %>%
    mutate(tidycoef = map(linearmod, tidy, conf.int = TRUE)) %>%
    select(borough, tidycoef) %>%
    unnest(cols = tidycoef) %>%
    filter(term == "gross_square_feet") %>%
    arrange(desc(estimate))
## # A tibble: 4 x 8
## # Groups:   borough [4]
##   borough       term   estimate std.error statistic   p.value conf.low conf.high
##   <chr>         <chr>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 brooklyn      gross~     709.     35.6      19.9  2.56e- 69     639.      779.
## 2 queens        gross~     379.      9.57     39.7  1.03e-272     361.      398.
## 3 staten_island gross~     226.      7.57     29.8  1.06e-145     211.      240.
## 4 bronx         gross~     204.     23.1       8.84 3.48e- 17     159.      250.

Some brief remarks on this results. The strongest estimate for the slope coefficient is for Brooklyn. This means that for every square feet, the price increases of about 709 dollars. All of the estimates are statistically significant, with a t-statistic much greater that 2. The most accurate model (the one which has the lowest RSE) is the Staten_island one.

Model performance

NY_twostories %>%
    group_by(borough) %>%
    nest() %>%
    mutate(linearmod = map(data, ~lm(sale_price ~ gross_square_feet, data = .))) %>%
    mutate(tidycoef = map(linearmod, tidy, conf.int = TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(augmented = map2(linearmod, data, augment)) %>%
    select(borough, augmented) %>%
    unnest(augmented) %>%
    ggplot(aes(gross_square_feet, .resid)) + geom_line() + facet_wrap(~borough, scales = "free") +
    ggtitle("Graph of the residuals") + scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
    theme_minimal()

NY_twostories %>%
    group_by(borough) %>%
    nest() %>%
    mutate(linearmod = map(data, ~lm(sale_price ~ gross_square_feet, data = .))) %>%
    mutate(tidycoef = map(linearmod, tidy, conf.int = TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(mod_summary = map(linearmod, glance)) %>%
    select(borough, mod_summary) %>%
    unnest(mod_summary) %>%
    arrange(desc(r.squared))
## # A tibble: 4 x 13
## # Groups:   borough [4]
##   borough       r.squared adj.r.squared   sigma statistic   p.value    df  logLik
##   <chr>             <dbl>         <dbl>   <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 staten_island     0.431         0.431 175515.     888.  1.06e-145     1 -15828.
## 2 brooklyn          0.376         0.375 712960.     396.  2.56e- 69     1  -9816.
## 3 queens            0.363         0.362 258066.    1573.  1.03e-272     1 -38391.
## 4 bronx             0.170         0.168 244883.      78.2 3.48e- 17     1  -5309.
## # ... with 5 more variables: AIC <dbl>, BIC <dbl>, deviance <dbl>,
## #   df.residual <int>, nobs <int>

These linear models, though significant statistically, capture poorly the variability contained in the response variable, with R squared ranging from 0.16 to 0.43. sigma, the RSE is also quite strong particularly for the brooklyn model, which as we have previously seen has the strongest outliers. A way of improvement would be to fit further models by borough and neighborhood, or also to add more predictors.

Possible improvements

For example, predicting prices with an interaction between the variables neighborhood and gross_square_feet as predictors already produces a much better model:

mod <- lm(sale_price ~ gross_square_feet:neighborhood, data = NY_twostories)
glance(mod)
## # A tibble: 1 x 12
##   r.squared adj.r.squared   sigma statistic p.value    df  logLik     AIC    BIC
##       <dbl>         <dbl>   <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1     0.712         0.702 255176.      68.4       0   174 -69005. 138361. 1.40e5
## # ... with 3 more variables: deviance <dbl>, df.residual <int>, nobs <int>

Using the model to make a prediction :

pred <- predict(mod, newdata = data.frame(neighborhood = "Baychester", gross_square_feet = 4374))

realprice <- filter(NY_twostories, neighborhood == "Baychester" & gross_square_feet ==
    4374) %>%
    pull(sale_price)

For a two store in Baychester area we predicted $805,750 instead of $715,000, with an error of $90,750.
